Here is one way to implement a brute force solution for the TSP in MATLAB:

```MATLAB
function distance = tsp_brute_force(cities)
    n = length(cities);
    min_distance = inf;
    best_order = NaN(1, n);

    % Iterate over all possible permutations of the cities
    for i = 1:factorial(n)
        order = nchoosek(1:n, n)(:, i);
        distance = 0;

        % Calculate the total distance of the tour
        for j = 1:n
            city1 = cities(order(j), :);
            city2 = cities(order(mod(j, n) + 1), :);
            distance = distance + dist(city1, city2);
        end

        % Keep track of the minimum distance and corresponding order
        if distance < min_distance
            min_distance = distance;
            best_order = order;
        end
    end
end

% Helper function to calculate the distance between two cities
function d = dist(city1, city2)
    d = sqrt(sum((city1 - city2).^2));
end
```

This implementation uses a brute force approach, in which it iterates over all possible permutations of the cities and calculates the total distance for each permutation. It keeps track of the minimum distance and the corresponding order of the cities.

The `tsp_brute_force` function takes as input a matrix of size `n x 2`, where `n` is the number of cities and each row represents the coordinates of a city. The output is the minimum total distance required to visit all cities and return to the original location.

